nodes.body:
Looks promising. Before merging #11469, this failed with a fatal error that correctly diagnosed the problem in #11469.

Now it just fails with about 40 complaints about our scripts. :-)

:v: semorrison can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded:
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/8337317014/job/22815857772)
  * [Check all files imported](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/8337317014/job/22815857589)
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/8337317014/job/22815857699)

I'm curious what this switch to `printf` protects against; I wonder if it should be `%q` instead? Either way, this is certainly not less safe than what we had before, and we don't need this to be perfectly safe anyway.

I'm responsible for this change and it was in response to a misinterpretation of the linter: the linter just pointed to the `run` line, and I guessed what the issue was.  After trying various changes, I think that it would have been enough to simply sprinkle more double quotes around variables, but by then I already made this change.
How did this work at all without these lines?
nit: I always assumed that `$(cat lean-toolchain)` with no spaces was more idiomatic
